name: Emerald catfish
remarks: The Emerald Cory Catfish is a very hardy and resilient fish.  Disease should not be a concern provided that you maintain the aquarium to standards.[6]

name: Peppered corydoras, salt and pepper catfish
Pygmy corydoras
remarks: A very peaceful species, that does not make an ideal community fish due to its small adult size. It is easily intimidated by larger tank mates and will not compete well with them for food.[10]

name: Threestripe corydoras, leopard catfish, false julii cory
Bristlenose pleco, bushynose pleco
remarks: The bristlenose genus has at least 59 identified species and many others yet to be named.[14] Males and female both have long "bristles" on their nose, the males having distinctly longer ones.

name: Whiptail catfish
remarks: It is a peaceful fish that is best kept in good sized groups (6+) in a mature tank with plenty of shady hiding spots amongst plants, driftwood, slate caves, and PVC pipes.[15]

name: Common pleco, suckermouth catfish, Amazon sailfin catfish
Common pleco, suckermouth catfish
remarks: Adults can become very territorial and aggressive towards each other. It is difficult to keep 2 adult common plecos together.[16]

name: Leopard sailfin pleco, clown sailfin pleco
Zebra pleco, L-046
remarks:
One of the most popular Hypancistrus species.
Endangered.[17]

name: Clown Pleco ( L104, L162, and LDA22)[18]
remarks: primary diet consists of wood, in aquaria this is provided in the source of drift wood. Will appreciate blanched vegetables, and/ or algae (wafer or live)[18]

name: Redtail catfish
min_tank_size: Needs at least a 2,600 US gallons (9,800 L) tank when mature, even though this does not provide them with the space to show their natural behaviour.[22]

name: Ornate Pimelodus
remarks: Similar to catfish but not in the same genus

name: Upside-down catfish
remarks: S. nigriventris prefers bottom feeding on Tubifex (or similar worms), but its main diet consists of algae.[23] The blotched upside-down catfish is well suited to aquariums because of its small size (typically 9 or 10 cm or less) and peaceful demeanor.[citation needed]

name: Walking catfish
remarks: The albino form is common in the aquarium trade. This fish can survive out of the water and "walk" as long as kept wet, for a very long time.[25]

name: Chao Phraya giant shark, giant pangasius
Black phantom tetra
remarks: The black phantom tetra enjoy being in groups of 6 or more and a slightly shaded tank. Males may claim small territories and occasionally minor battles may occur. The Phantom tetra goes well with other tetras of similar size. They also prefer floating plants.[27]

name: Black tetra, skirt tetra
remarks: A highly spirited fish that may occasionally chase its own species as well as harass slow moving fish with long fins. This fish is very hardy and can stand a variety of water qualities. Disease is not a big problem with the black tetra. The black tetra is also known as the black skirt tetra. The female black tetra is more robust and larger than the male.[29]

name: Bleeding heart tetra
remarks: The bleeding heart tetra is distinguished by the small red spot on both sides of the fish. This fish is very prone to diseases, and can grow larger than most tetra species.[30]

name: Cardinal tetra
remarks: Similar to the Neon Tetra, but slightly larger and doesn't prefer to school as much. They need much larger tanks, although their temperament is similar.[31]

name: Cave tetra, blind tetra
remarks: The cave tetra is the blind cave form of the Mexican tetra. This tetra prefers low to moderate lighting.[32]

name: Ember tetra
remarks: Ember tetras have been known to live ten years or more. May become stressed by the presence of larger fish.[33]

name: Green neon tetra
remarks: Similar to Neon Tetras and Cardinal Tetras, they are the same to Neon Tetras beside having a green tiny near their top dorsal fin[35]

name: Neon tetra
remarks: Neon tetras must be kept in groups of at least a half-dozen, as they are a shoaling species. With peaceful dispositions, they are also able to be kept with other species of non-aggressive fish.[36]

name: Royal tetra
remarks: Possesses an adipose fin allowing it to be differentiated from the Emperor tetra [38]

name: Rummy-nose tetra
remarks: This common name is used for three different species of schooling fish with similar patterns: Hemigrammus rhodostomus, Hemigrammus bleheri, and Petitella georgiae.

name: X-ray tetra
remarks: Also just called the X-ray fish.

name: Congo tetra
remarks: Peaceful but may scare shy species with its active swimming and large adult size. Recommended for most community tanks however. Do not keep congo tetras with fin-nipping species as the spectacular fins of the males will be destroyed.[39]

name: Common hatchetfish
remarks: Requires a varied diet including fruit flies[40][41]

name: Marbled hatchetfish
remarks: Requires a varied diet including fruit flies[41][40]

name: Silver dollar
remarks: The name "silver dollar" may also refer to Metynnis hypsauchen, Metynnis maculatus, or other related fishes.

name: Cobalt blue cichlid, cobalt zebra cichlid
Masked Julie
size: 15 cm (5.9 in) fem / 10 cm (3.9 in) male

name: Julie cichlid
size: 15 cm (5.9 in) fem / 10 cm (3.9 in) male

remarks: A small shell-dwelling cichlid from Lake Tanganyika. Very similar to N. multifsciatus but similis has striping from the body continue to the head

name: Lifalili jewel cichlid, blood-red jewel cichlid
Blue ram, German ram, German Ramirezi
remarks: These small and colorful fish require precise water parameters, and if you don't meet those parameters, your fish could be severely impacted.[43]

name: Midas cichlid
remarks: commonly confused with red devil cichlids, but it is an entirely different species [44]

name: Angelfish
remarks: In an enclosed tank habitat, the fish's territorial, aggressive nature is heightened, so don't house angelfish with shy species that are intimidated by pushy, boisterous fish.[45]

name: Oscar
remarks: Many people that purchase these fish do not realize that the fish could grow to a foot long (30 cm) within a year. Due to their fast growth rate and large size as an adult, they are often kept in aquariums that are too small for them.[46]

name: Uaru, waroo
remarks: Also known as the Triangle Cichlid.

name: Blood parrot cichlid
remarks: Not considered a separate species of cichlid but a hybrid.[47]

name: Flowerhorn cichlid
remarks: Not considered a separate species of cichlid but a hybrid.[47]

name: Denison's barb, red line torpedo barb
Tiger barb, sumatra barb
remarks: Keep in shoals of 8 or 10 to prevent aggression[48]

name: Bala shark
remarks: Grows large, needs lots of swimming room and is a schooling fish so a 125 gallon would be good for 3-4[49]

name: Siamese algae eater, fringe barb
remarks: Many other fish in the order Cypriniformes are also sold under this name. Very likely to jump out of the aquarium especially after reaching adult size. Very useful for getting rid of algae when it is young but prefer fish food upon reaching adulthood.[50]

name: Cambodian log sucker, false Siamese algae eater
algae eater
remarks: This species may be sold under a variety of common names, including Siamese algae eater, Chinese algae eater, golden algae eater, or sucking loach. A gold colored form also exists.

name: Chili rasbora
remarks: Should be kept in acidic water which can be difficult to maintain for most beginners in the aquarium hobby.[51]

name: Harlequin rasbora
remarks: Also known as Harlequin tetra or Harlequin barb.

name: Red-striped rasbora
remarks: Range: Sumatra

name: Pearl danio
remarks: subspecies:blue-redstripe danio, Kedah danio

name: Zebra danio
remarks: there are many variations of this fish: leopard danio, the spotted colour morph, and GloFish, the genetically modified fluorescent fish.

name: Goldfish
remarks: variations: Black Moor, Bubble Eye, Butterfly Tail, Calico, Celestial Eye, Comet, Common, Fantail, Lionchu, Lionhead, Oranda, Panda Moor, Pearlscale, Pompom, Ranchu, Ryukin, Shubunkin, Telescope eye, Veiltail.

name: Saddle-back Loach
remarks: The Saddleback Loach will thrive in an aquarium with a good amount of water flow and aeration, considerable amounts of hiding places formed by rocks or driftwood and smooth pebbles and stones to graze on.[52]

name: Weather Loach[53]
remarks: Sensitive to changes in barometric pressure[55]

name: Kuhli loach, coolie loach
remarks: The natural habitat of the kuhli loach is the sandy beds of slow-moving rivers and clean mountain streams. They are a social fish and are typically found in small clusters (they are not schooling fish but enjoy the company of their species), but are cautious and nocturnal by nature and swim near the bottom where they feed around obstacles. Kuhli loaches are scavengers, so they will eat anything that reaches the bottom.[citation needed]

name: Dwarf botia
remarks: Formerly named Botia sidthimunki.

name: Bengal loach
remarks: Also known as the Queen loach.

name: Skunk loach
remarks: Formerly named Botia morleti

name: Borneo hillstream loach
remarks: Eats mainly algae. High oxygen level and water quality are greatly appreciated in addition to a strong current (but not needed as many sources claim)[56]

name: Tiger hillstream loach
remarks: Eats mainly algae. High oxygen level and water quality are greatly appreciated in addition to a strong current (but not needed as many sources claim)[56]

name: Butterfly hillstream loach
remarks: Eats mainly algae. High oxygen level and water quality are greatly appreciated in addition to a strong current (but not needed as many sources claim)[56]

name: Guppy
remarks: Many color and tail pattern varieties exist. They generally need a ratio of 1 male to 2 females or more. All guppies and mollies are hardy fish that tolerate lower oxygen levels and temperatures than most aquarium fish, give birth to live young, and readily breed in home tanks.[58] can live in full sea water[59]

name: Black molly
remarks: Can live in full sea water[59]

name: Sailfin molly
remarks: Gold and silver varieties commonly found; also thrive in brackish water/ full sea water[59]

name: Dalmatian molly
remarks: The dalmatian molly is a hybrid color variation that can be generated by crossing some species of Poecilia, like P. sphenops and P. latipinna. The variety "Dalmatian" is spotted alike to a Dalmatian dog. Can live in full sea water[59]

name: Lyretail Molly
remarks: Lyretail Mollies are available in all of these species, can be cross bred with any species of Molly. Can live in full sea water[59]

name: Wrestling halfbeak
remarks: Wrestling Halfbeaks are best kept in groups, composed of either a single male with several females, or, in more spacious quarters with ample visual barriers, larger mixed groups containing at least six males.

name: Clown Killifish, rocket killifish
remarks:
However, for natural behaviour, a dozen individuals kept in an aquarium of at least 50 litres will be ideal. Compose your group with a ratio of one male to two or three females.
For maintenance with other species, choose small, peaceful fish that like stagnant water (no Cory doras!).[61]

name: Bluefin Notho, Rachow's Notho, Rainbow Notho
American Flagfish
remarks: Native to SE United States

name: Siamese fighting fish (sometimes Betta, esp. US)
remarks: Betta is the name of the genus that includes more than 60 species other than the Siamese fighting fish.

name: Dwarf gourami
remarks: Suitable for small to mid-sized aquariums but cannot compete with more aggressive fish and males kept together may fight. Several color varieties available. Massive inbreeding has led to high rates of Dwarf gourami iridovirus (DGIV) in pet store fish.[63]

remarks: Illegal to possess live in the USA without a permit[65]

name: Red rainbowfish
remarks: Almost all rainbowfish species are bred in captivity and wild populations may be protected.[66]

name: Duboulayi's rainbowfish
remarks: a.k.a. Crimson-Spotted rainbowfish

name: Forktail blue-eye
remarks: These fish need a larger aquarium than their size suggests. Though they only grow to a length of about 2 inches, they are happiest in groups of 8 – 10 or more, and they appreciate lots of swimming space.[67]

name: Peacock gudgeon, Peacock goby
remarks: A little territorial with its own kind but is suitable for many communities of small, peaceful fish. Ideal tankmates are other species from Papua New Guinea, such as Popondetta sp. rainbowfishes; but tetras, rasboras, Corydoras cats and virtually any other small peaceful species are also suitable.[68]
